@prefix : <#> .
@prefix schema: <http://schema.org/> .
@prefix xsd: <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .

: a schema:CreativeWork ;
    schema:about :noUnauthorizedDeletion .

:noUnauthorizedDeletion a schema:HowTo ;
    schema:name "No Unauthorized File Deletion"@en ;
    schema:description "Files must never be deleted without the user's explicit, unambiguous approval. This rule was established after an agent deleted okf-infographic-claude_sonnet_4_6-1.html from Claude Generated/webpages/ without explicit approval during the OKF model attribution correction task on 2026-06-15."@en ;
    schema:dateCreated "2026-06-15T13:00:00Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:dateModified "2026-06-15T13:00:00Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:step :step1, :step2, :step3 .

:step1 a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 1 ;
    schema:name "Flag, don't delete"@en ;
    schema:text """When you encounter a file that appears deletable (stale leftover, wrong name, wrong directory, superseded version, temporary artifact):

1. State the file's full path to the user
2. Explain why it looks like it could be deleted
3. Ask the user explicitly whether to delete it
4. Wait for explicit approval before taking any action

Never delete first and explain later. Deletion is irreversible."""@en .

:step2 a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 2 ;
    schema:name "What counts as a deletion"@en ;
    schema:text """This rule covers:
  - Direct file deletion (rm, unlink, fs.unlink, etc.)
  - Overwriting a file in a way that destroys its prior content (write without read-first verification)
  - Moving a file to trash without asking
  - Moving a file to a different directory under the assumption it's "wrong"
  - Any operation whose net effect is that a file the user placed or left in a location is no longer there

Cross-reference: :step-approval (preferences.ttl position 1) — the broader approval rule."""@en .

:step3 a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 3 ;
    schema:name "No implicit consent"@en ;
    schema:text """Do not infer deletion approval from:
  - Prior task instructions (even if the task involves renaming or reorganizing)
  - The file being a "stale leftover" from a completed operation
  - The file having an "incorrect" name or location
  - The assumption that the user "wouldn't want" the old version
  - Any context outside of the user's explicit, specific instruction to delete that file

The user's filesystem state is their own. What looks like cleanup to an agent may be data loss to the user."""@en .
